Part 1 : DATA ACCESS

The very first step to begin with the project is to first scrap the data from an external website (wikipedia), read it in R and work with its tables. Here I create 4 tables to get the data from 4 decades of Grammy nominations. I convert them into list of length 1 so that it’s reasy to reduce them into one table.
#read webpage for Grammy Awards
webpage <- read_html("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grammy_Award_for_Record_of_the_Year")

#copy XPATH for table of 1980s
XPATH80 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[5]'

# run the following to create table of songs from 1980s
table_1980 <- 
  webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH80) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)

#creating a list for the songs from 1980s
d1980 <- table_1980[[1]]


# copy xpath for table of 1990s
XPATH90 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[6]'

# run the following to create table of songs from 1990s
table_1990 <- 
  webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH90) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)

#creating a list for the songs from 1990s
d1990 <- table_1990[[1]]


# copy xpath for table of 2000s
XPATH00 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[7]'

# run the following to create table of songs from 2000s
table_2000 <- 
  webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH00) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)

#creating a list for the songs from 2000s
d2000 <- table_2000[[1]]


# copy xpath for table of 2010s
XPATH10 <- '/html/body/div[3]/div[3]/div[5]/div[1]/table[8]'

# run the following to create table of songs from 2010s

  webpage %>%
  html_nodes(xpath = XPATH10) %>%
  html_table(fill = TRUE)

#creating a list for the songs from 2010s
d2010 <- table_2010[[1]]

Part 2: DATA WRANGLING (CONTD.)

Create data set that combines all the records into one data frame called combined_table. Now, I clean the table to rename columns such as Year[I] to year, Record to track and Artist(s) to artist. I also extract year variable without the subscript and to remove footnotes using the extract function and regular expression (regex=“([[:digit:]]{4})”), which keeps just the first 4 digits of the year variable and not [44],[46],etc. Finally lyrics are added from the genius package to the table with the tidy data.
# create a combined table containing songs from all decades (1980s to 2010s)
combined_table <-
  Reduce(function(x, y) merge(x, y, all=TRUE), list(table_1980, table_1990,table_2000, table_2010)) %>%
  na.omit(combined_table)%>%
  rename(year = Year.I., track= Record, artist= Artist.s.)

# clean the table to get tidy data  
clean_table<-
  extract(combined_table,col = "year" , into= "year", regex = "([[:digit:]]{4})" )
  
final_clean_table<-
  subset(clean_table, select = -c(Production.team) )


# using the genius package to add lyrics to the tidy data table called lyrics_final, containing songs from all decades (1980s to 2000s) 
lyrics_final<-
  final_clean_table %>%
  add_genius(artist, track, type = "lyrics")

GRAPH 1: Here I start by creating a new variable called decade by using the mutate function and ifelse conditions. # creating a new variable called decade using mutate function in the table lyrics_final
lyrics_final<-
  lyrics_final%>%
  mutate (lyrics_final, decade= ifelse(year=="1980","1980s",ifelse(year=="1981", "1980s", ifelse(year== "1982", "1980s", ifelse(year=="1983", "1980s",ifelse(year=="1984","1980s", ifelse(year=="1985","1980s",ifelse(year=="1986","1980s",ifelse(year=="1987","1980s",ifelse(year=="1988","1980s",ifelse(year=="1989","1980s",ifelse(year=="1990","1990s",ifelse(year=="1991", "1990s", ifelse(year== "1992", "1990s", ifelse(year=="1993", "1990s",ifelse(year=="1994","1990s", ifelse(year=="1995","1990s",ifelse(year=="1996","1990s",ifelse(year=="1997","1990s",ifelse(year=="1998","1990s",ifelse(year=="1999","1990s",ifelse(year=="2000","2000s",ifelse(year=="2001", "2000s", ifelse(year== "2002", "2000s", ifelse(year=="2003", "2000s",ifelse(year=="2004","2000s", ifelse(year=="2005","2000s",ifelse(year=="2006","2000s",ifelse(year=="2007","2000s",ifelse(year=="2008","2000s",ifelse(year=="2009","2000s","2010s")))))))))))))))))))))))))))))))

# creating a table to unnest the lyrics of the song and count the words per song in order to prepare Graph 1
Combine_decade<-
  lyrics_final%>%
  unnest_tokens(word,lyric)%>%
  group_by(decade,track)%>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)%>%
  summarise(total=n())
`summarise()` regrouping output by 'decade' (override with `.groups` argument)
# using the Combine_decade data frame to create a boxplot of words per Grammy nominated song by decade
 ggplot(Combine_decade)+
  aes(x=decade, y=total, fill=decade)+
  geom_boxplot(show.legend = FALSE)+
  labs(title = "Words per Grammy Nominated Song by Decade",x="Decade", y="Words per Song")

(CONTD.) Part2

This is the part of the project I enjoyed doing because I had only enough help to think and reach this solution. For the next section we need to filter out stop words from the song lyrics. For this use the unnested lyrics and anti_join function to filter out the stop words given in the dataset stop_words. Next, I use a filter function to further filter out the 11 stops words which were ba, du,yeah, da, ya, ooh, gonna, na, uh, la and hol, using & operator to make the code compact and use only one filter statement.
# this process filters stop words from the lyrics of the songs , we start by unnesting the lyrics
unnesting_lyrics<-
  lyrics_final%>%
  unnest_tokens(word,lyric)

# filter the stop words using the stop_words data set loaded at the beginning 
filtered_words<-
  unnesting_lyrics%>%
  anti_join(stop_words)
Joining, by = "word"
# filter 11 more stop words, which are ba, du,yeah, da, ya, ooh, gonna, na, uh, la, hol
filtered_words_final<-
  filtered_words%>%
  #count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  filter((word!= 'ba') & (word!='du') &(word!='yeah') & (word!='da') &(word!='ya') & (word!='ooh') &(word!='gonna') &(word!='na') &(word!='uh') & (word!='la') & (word!='hol'))

# get a dataframe for the top 10 words overall, that is diregarding decade
topten_words<-
  filtered_words_final%>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10)
Selecting by n
# plot the second graph using the topten_words
topten_words%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(word, -n),y=n)) +
  geom_col(fill='blue')+
  labs(title="Ten Most Popular Words of Grammy Nominated Songs from 1980 - 2019", x="Word",y="Count")

# creating a table with the net sentiment score for each year
sentiment_score1<-
  filtered_words_final%>%
  select(decade,word,year)%>%
  right_join(sentiments, by="word")%>%
  mutate(s_score= ifelse(sentiment=="positive",1,0))%>%
  group_by(decade,year,s_score)%>%
  summarise(net_score=sum(s_score))%>%
  na.omit(sentiment_score1)
`summarise()` regrouping output by 'decade', 'year' (override with `.groups` argument)
# plot foe net sentiment score by year
ggplot(sentiment_score1) +
 aes(x = year, fill = decade, weight = net_score) +
 geom_bar() +
 scale_fill_brewer(palette = "PiYG") +
 labs(x = "Year", y = "Net Sentiment", title = "Net Sentiment Score by Year") +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=c("1980","1990","2000","2010","2020"))+
 theme_minimal()

GRAPH 4: This graph is a bar graph of net sentiment score by year with the bars a different color across decade. I used the right_join function to join the data frame filtered_words_final which contains the filtered tidy data and the data set sentiments. To recode the sentiment values (positive and negative) into 1 for positive and 0 for negative, I created a variable s_score using the mutate function and calculated the net_score. The graph is representing the net sentiment score by year but the x-axis had been modified to depict a decade using the scale_x_discrete function.

# creating another table with the mean sentiment score per decade
sentiment_score2<-
  filtered_words_final%>%
  select(decade,word,year)%>%
  right_join(sentiments, by="word")%>%
  mutate(s_score= ifelse(sentiment=="positive",1,0))%>%
  group_by(decade,)%>%
  summarise(mean_score=mean(s_score))%>%
  na.omit(sentiment_score1)
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
# plot for the mean sentiment score by decade
ggplot(sentiment_score2) +
 aes(x = decade, fill = decade, weight = mean_score) +
 geom_bar() +
 scale_fill_hue() +
 labs(x = "Decade", y = "Mean Sentiment Score", title = "Mean Sentiment Score by Decade ") +
 theme_gray() +
 theme(legend.position = "none")

GRAPH 5: A bar graph of mean sentiment score per decade without a legend. Again I joined the two data sets, filtered_words_final and sentiments to find the mean sentiment score by decade and greated a labled bar graph with each decade having a different colour.

# plot and regression line for the net sentiment score by year of the Grammy nominated records from 1980-2019 with linear model fit 
ggplot(data=sentiment_score1,aes(x=year, y=net_score)) +
   geom_point(aes(color= decade), size=1)+
   geom_smooth(na.rm = TRUE, fullrange= TRUE, aes(group=1),colour="blue", size=0.5, se=FALSE)+
  labs(title="Net Sentiment Score by Year of Grammy Nominated Records from 1980 - 2019 with Linear Model Fit", x="Year", y="Net Sentiment")+
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=c("1980","1990","2000","2010","2020"))+
   theme_minimal()
